    ------DBMS-------    (Database Management System)
    |              |
Relational   Non-Relational
  DBMS            DBMS

SQL (Structured query language) is the programming language used in RDBMS Softwares like MySQL, Oracle database, SSMS, PostgreSQL, etc

--> Categories for SQL:-
- DDL : Data Definition Language : create, drop, alter, truncate
- DML : Data Manipulation Language : insert, update, delete
- DQL : Data Query Language : select
- DCL : Data Control Language : grant, revoke
- TCL : Transaction Control Language : begin transaction, savepoint, commit, rollback


--> Database objects:-
Database Objects are the defined, named structures that are used to store, manage, and reference data within a RDBMS.

1. Data Storage Objects (The Structure) - These objects are used to directly store or structure the raw data
- Tables
- Indexes
- Views
- Sequences

2. Programmatic Objects (The Functionality) - These objects contain executable code or logic to perform specific tasks
- Stored procedures
- Functions
- Triggers

3. Security and Other Objects - These objects manage access, security, and administrative tasks.
- Schemas
- Users & roles


--> Data Integrity Constraints:-
- PRIMARY KEY
- FOREIGN KEY
- NOT NULL
- UNIQUE
- CHECK
- DEFAULT

1) Primary Key
- Uniquely identifies every single row in a table (entity integrity)
- It wont take repeated value
- It wont take any null value
- A table can only have 1 primary key

2) Foreign key
- The foreign key in the child table references to the primary key in the parent table
- Referential Integrity. Ensures relationships between tables are valid, preventing "orphan" records.
- Allows nulls
- A table can have multiple foreign keys

3) Not null
- Restricts a column from accepting a NULL value
- (Domain Integrity)

4) Unique
- Ensures that all values in a column are different.
- It can take null values
- (Domain Integrity)

5) Check
- Restricts the range of values that can be placed in a column.
- (Domain Integrity)

6) Default
- Provides a default value for a column if no value is explicitly specified during an INSERT operation.
- (Domain Integrity)


--> Categories of datatypes:-
1) String
  - char(n) : A FIXED length string
  - varchar(n) : A VARIABLE length string

2) Numeric
  - int : for whole numbers (integers)
  - numeric(n) : defining the total number of digits (n)
  - real : for number with unknown decimal places
  - bit [boolean] : 0 (False), 1 (True)

3) Date & Time
  - date [YYYY-MM-DD] 
  - time [HH:MM:SS] 
  - datetime [YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS]

--> Aggregate functions:-

The most commonly used SQL aggregate functions are
- MIN() - returns the smallest value within the selected column
- MAX() - returns the largest value within the selected column
- COUNT() - returns the number of rows in a set
- SUM() - returns the total sum of a numerical column
- AVG() - returns the average value of a numerical column
Aggregate functions ignore null values (except for COUNT(*)).


--> Comments in sql:-
1) -- double hyphen is for a single line comment
2) /* and this
    is a 
    multiline comment*/

--> DDL:-
A. --- CREATE Command ---
1) create database {databasename};
2) use {databasename};
3) create table {tablename} (
    {attribute_name1} {datatype} {contraint [if any]},
    {attribute_name2} {datatype} {contraint [if any]},
    {attribute_name3} {datatype} {contraint [if any]},
    {attribute_name4} {datatype} {contraint [if any]}
    );

B. --- ALTER COMMAND ---
1) add/drop columns
2) add/drop constraints
3) modify columns
4) rename table/columns

c. --- DROP Command ---
1) drop database {databasename};
2) drop table {table_name};

D. --- TRUNCATE Command ---
1) truncate table {table_name};


